<header class="splash">
    <div class="splash__intro">
        <img src="_assets/biotope-logo.svg" alt="" class="splash__logo">
        <div class="splash__content">
            <h1 class="splash__biotope">biotope</h1>
            <h2 class="splash__uitoolchain">ui toolchain</h2>
            <p class="splash__claim">
                One web component library. As many worlds as you want. Decide what the future looks like.
            </p>
            <bio-button title="Explore" modifier="whiteText"
                data-resources="[{paths: ['components/BioButton/index.js']}]" url="#resources"></bio-button>
            <bio-button title="See Docs" modifier="blue whiteText"
                data-resources="[{paths: ['components/BioButton/index.js']}]" url="https://build.biotope.sh">
            </bio-button>
        </div>
    </div>
</header>

<section class="benefits">
    <div class="row row--reducedWidth">
        <div class="col">
            <div class="benefits__claim">
                <img src="../_assets/intro-main.svg" alt="">
                <div>
                    <h2>
                        One Web Component Library. As Many Words As You Want.
                    </h2>
                    <bio-paragraph data-resources="[{paths: ['components/BioParagraph/index.js']}]">
                       The superpower of Web Components is that they are reusable. Build them once and use them in any project across your whole ocmpany. 
                       Biotope helps you build Web Components quickly, makes sure they work tohether and reconciles them into a single library. 
                       This in turn gives you a superpower: Lasting control of your entire UI.
                    </bio-paragraph>
                    <bio-button class="js-openModal" title="Who's behind biotope" modifier="long"
                        data-resources="[{paths: ['components/BioButton/index.js']}]"></bio-button>
                </div>
            </div>
            <div class="benefits__container">
                <bio-benefit data-resources="[{paths: ['components/BioBenefit/index.js']}]"
                    imgsrc="../../_assets/framework-agnostic.svg" title="Framework agnostic">
                    Biotope works with any framework - Angular, React, Vue, etc. so there won't be any compatability issues. Use whichever you want. Or switch when it suits you.
                </bio-benefit>
                <bio-benefit data-resources="[{paths: ['components/BioBenefit/index.js']}]"
                    imgsrc="../../_assets/future-proof.svg" title="Futureproof">
                    Web Components are a standard web technology. Because there is no coupling to the apps or websites for which they are used, 
                    your library of Web Components theoretically lives on forever.
                </bio-benefit>
                <bio-benefit data-resources="[{paths: ['components/BioBenefit/index.js']}]"
                    imgsrc="../../_assets/icon-open-source.svg" title="100% Open Source">
                    Biotope's entire toolchain is free. it is maintained by a community of professional developers.
                </bio-benefit>
            </div>
        </div>
    </div>
</section>

